Jinja2 is a template engine used in Python web frameworks like Flask.
It allows you to write HTML and insert Python variables, conditions, loops, etc. inside HTML files.
In simple words:
➡️ Jinja2 = HTML + Python logic
So Flask sends data from app.py → HTML template, and Jinja2 displays it.
1. Basic Jinja2 Syntax
1️⃣ Print Python variable
{{ variable }}
..........................................................................................................
Example:
app.py

from flask import Flask, render_template

app = Flask(__name__)

@app.route("/")
def home():
    return render_template("welcome.html", name="Anand")
..................
welcome.html
<h1>Welcome {{ name }}</h1>
................
Output:
Welcome Anand
.............................................................................................
2. Jinja2 Condition (if-else)

Jinja2 allows conditions similar to Python.

{% if condition %}
{% else %}
{% endif %}
...............................
Example:
app.py

@app.route("/result")
def result():
    return render_template("welcome.html", is_topper=True)
...........................
welcome.html

{% if is_topper %}
<p>You are a topper</p>
{% else %}
<p>You need to work hard</p>
{% endif %}
...............
Output:
You are a topper
.........................................................................................
3. Jinja2 Template Inheritance
In large websites many pages share the same layout like:

Navbar
Footer
Header
Instead of writing it again and again we create a base template.
....................................
Concept:
base.html → main layout
other pages → extend base.html
....................................
